questions.question:
Consider the following two transactions T1 and T2:

T1: read(A);
    read(B);
    If A = 0 then B <- B + 1;
    write(B);

T2: read(B);
    read(A);
    If B != 0 then A <- A - 1;
    write(A);

Which of the following schemes, using shared and exclusive locks, satisfy the requirements for strict two phase locking for the above transactions?

A.
S1: lock S(A);         S2: lock S(B);
    read(A);                read(B);
    lock S(B);              lock X(A);
    read(B);                read(A);
    If A = 0               If B != 0
    then B <- B + 1;       then A <- A - 1;
    write(B);              write(A);
    commit;                commit;
    unlock(A);             unlock(B);
    unlock(B);             unlock(A);

B.
S1: lock S(A);         S2: lock S(B);
    read(A);                read(B);
    lock X(B);              lock X(A);
    read(B);                read(A);
    If A = 0               If B != 0
    then B <- B + 1;       then A <- A - 1;
    write(B);              write(A);
    commit;                commit;
    unlock(A);             unlock(B);
    unlock(B);             unlock(A);

C.
S1: lock S(A);         S2: lock S(B);
    read(A);                read(B);
    lock X(B);              lock X(A);
    read(B);                read(A);
    If A = 0               If B != 0
    then B <- B + 1;       then A <- A - 1;
    write(B);              write(A);
    commit;                commit;
    unlock(A);             unlock(B);
    unlock(B);             unlock(A);

D.
S1: lock S(A);         S2: lock S(B);
    read(A);                read(B);
    lock X(B);              lock X(A);
    read(B);                read(A);
    If A = 0               If B != 0
    then B <- B + 1;       then A <- A - 1;
    write(B);              write(A);
    unlock(A);             unlock(B);
    commit;                commit;
    unlock(B);             unlock(A);
